However, as difficult as these decisions are, we are hopeful that the economy will bounce back quickly and that we may be able to release some of these funds as the year goes on.

In addition to these vetoes, we are restricting over $448 million from the 2021 budget to ensure we are financially prepared for this fiscal year.

As we adjusted our budget projections, we left no agency, division, or program out of a review.

We had to restrict over $430 million in 2020 spending to balance the budget, and we will continue to face budget shortfalls in fiscal year 2021.

With that said, we are vetoing 17 items totaling almost $11 million today.

For FY 2020, state revenues are going to finish approximately 7% down from last year.

We expect to be almost $1 billion dollars below what we forecast in January.

As everyone is well aware, COVID-19 has SEVERELY impacted our economy and our expectations.

We could have never imagined this is where we would be today, but we have had to face the reality and make some extremely difficult decisions about our budget.

Today, I signed the Fiscal Year 2021 budget bills passed by the General Assembly.

From May 1, to June 10, total hospitalizations have fallen by 43% statewide.

As more people recover, ICU beds and ventilators continue to become available.
Pillar 3 was hospital capacity – our hospitals were NOT overwhelmed, and we converted a hotel into a hospital in just 11 days thanks to the @Missouri_NG and the Army Corps of Engineers.

Pillar 2 was PPE – we continue to receive & distribute PPE, and our PPE marketplace received national recognition.

We currently have over 100 hospitals, 436 suppliers, and more than 1,500 healthcare providers, MO businesses & organizations registered in the PPE marketplace.

Pillar 1 was testing – we went from testing only a handful of people each day to an average of approximately TEN THOUSAND tests per day over the past 2 weeks.

Since April 20, weekly testing has increased more than 220%.

We are just over 90 days since our 1st case in Missouri, and I am so proud of our citizens, businesses & communities across the state for doing their part and using common sense.

Thanks to you, we have overcome ALL of these challenges and have met our four pillars to reopen.
We ALL know how to do this by now, and it is up to us to take personal responsibility for our own actions.

The virus is still out there, and it is still extremely important for everyone to continue social distancing. 
◦Be proactive.
◦Avoid large, congested crowds. 
◦And if you can’t social distance, take extra precautions to protect yourself and those around you.

We have full confidence that Missouri is prepared and ready to move forward.

But I want to be clear – just because we’re fully reopening the state DOES NOT MEAN that the steps we’ve taken so far should be forgotten.

During today’s COVID-19 briefing, we announced more than $209 million in additional expenditure restrictions due to COVID-19.

🔗

Even with everything going on around us we must keep pushing forward. We've been through tough times before, and we will get through this by working together for a better future for our families and future generations.

In the short term, we will be able to utilize $187 million in federal funds distributed as Title 1 dollars to help a majority of school districts.
It is important to make these decisions now so school districts can adjust before next school year. Our intent is to withhold now and avoid withholds once school begins.
We have had numerous conversations with DESE, the State Board of Education, superintendents, and administrators to keep them as informed as possible throughout the COVID-19 crisis.

Before COVID-19, one of our priorities for this year was to start looking at ways to increase teacher pay.

As difficult as these decisions are, we are experiencing an unprecedented economic downturn, which means we are having to make unprecedented adjustments in our budget.

I have ALWAYS been a strong supporter of education. These were extremely difficult decisions I never thought I would have to make a few months ago.

I have consistently voted for fully funded education budgets. As Governor, I have proposed budgets that fully funded education.

In order to make it as fair as possible, I've waived the hold harmless statute.

The waiver of this statute means hold harmless districts are not exempt from these withholdings. ALL local ed agencies, including charter schools, will share proportionately in this budget shortfall.

For Department of Elementary & Secondary Ed, over $131 million dollars will be restricted, including $123 million dollars from the Foundation Formula.

Fully funded, the Foundation Formula is over $3.5 billion dollars.
Of this round of restrictions, over $41 million dollars in general revenue will be withheld from the Department of Higher Education and Workforce Development.

These restrictions include reduced funding for:
◦ Office of Administration
◦ Department of Corrections
◦ Department of Health & Sr Services
◦ Department of Social Services
◦ Department of Higher Ed. & Workforce Development
◦ Department of Elementary & Secondary Ed.

We have ALREADY had to withhold over $220 million dollars due to budget concerns resulting from COVID-19.

In addition to these restrictions, we will be restricting another $209 million dollars by the end of June.

Our unemployment rate, which has been at near-historic lows for much of my administration, rose from 3.9% to 9.7% in April.

We’ve had to face the reality of the situation and make some extremely difficult decisions regarding our state budget.

We are now expecting significant revenue declines, some of which may be larger than those experienced during the Great Recession.

Just to put things into perspective, Missouri saw a decline of over 300,000 jobs between March and April alone – a decline of over 10%.

When we began this fiscal year, we anticipated economic growth, and we based our budget on that growth.

However, it goes without saying that COVID-19 has had SEVERE impacts on our anticipated economic growth. This is truly unlike anything we have ever experienced before.
Last year, we were able to leave $100 million dollars on the bottom line in order to respond to any unanticipated revenue declines and we are thankful we did after everything that has happened.

We have, at many times, had more jobs available than we have had people to fill them. Because of this, we've been able to focus on our workforce & infrastructure.

During these times, we've also been able to put forward responsible & conservative budgets to the General Assembly.

It's hard to believe that it's been just over 75 days since our 1st COVID-19 case in MO, and that we’re almost halfway through 2020.

Up until this point in my administration, we have been very fortunate to have a booming economy with record low unemployment and high wage growth.
EVERY citizen deserves to be safe and protected, and to change things we must not tear each other down, but stand together peacefully.

The goal with box-in testing is to go into these high-risk facilities where there has been at least one positive case and execute facility-wide testing.

...the Department of Veterans Affairs, Fannie Mae, and Freddie Mac was put in place for 60 days starting March 18.

The funds can also be used for eviction prevention assistance, including rapid re-housing, housing counseling, and rental deposit assistance.

These funds can specifically be used to help unsheltered homeless, sheltered homeless, or those at risk of homelessness.

God bless the great state of Missouri!

For the sake of ALL Missourians, be smart, be responsible, and FOLLOW THIS ORDER.

STAY-AT-HOME MISSOURI!
To WIN this battle against COVID-19, it is going to take EACH ONE OF US doing our part.

This is not about any one individual person. 

This is about our families, friends, and neighbors. This is about the ENTIRE state of Missouri.

Therefore, my order will provide a clear framework to allow businesses to operate, but they will have to follow social distancing measures.

By tightening the exemptions that led to an unintended funnel effect, my order goes further than ANY directive in the state.
Medical experts have told us is that some essential businesses have become hotbeds for transmission as people flock to those locations and risk spreading the virus even further.

Many orders were put into place early on in other states and many cities without thinking about the un-intended consequences. 

Hundreds of businesses were declared essential and THOUSANDS were declared non-essential.

Over one hundred THOUSAND people have filed for unemployment, and I’m sure they all would tell you they thought their jobs were essential.

Their spouses, families, and everyone who depends on them, thought their jobs were essential.

This power is something I think should be rare for government to ever take advantage of … and for one person to make the decision for 6 million Missourians without due process, jeopardizing their liberties.

It is not just about encouraging people to stay at home. 

It is about having the power as Governor to pick winners and losers … and whether I feel it is appropriate for me to use that power by determining who is essential and who is not.

This state means so much to me. There are 6 million of us that call Missouri home. 

We live in small towns and large cities, and our diversity is one of the greatest advantages we have as a state.

○ All individuals in the State of Missouri shall avoid social gatherings of more than ten (10) people.
○ All public and charter schools must remain closed. 
○ This order also covers the timeframe of existing municipal and county orders.

This Order requires:

○ Individuals currently residing within the State of Missouri shall avoid leaving their homes or places of residence.

Fortunately, Missouri’s COVID-19 death rate is still below 1 percent as of today.
I am saddened to report Missouri has 19 deaths at this time. Our hearts go out to their families and their loved ones.

Of the Missouri citizens who tested positive, approximately 22 percent have required hospitalization. 

This means the remaining 78 percent are recovering at home or have already recovered.
As of today, out the 24,727 people that have been tested in Missouri’s total population of approximately 6 MILLION, there have been 2,113 positive cases of COVID-19.

On March 21, I ordered a STATEWIDE “social distancing” Order requiring social gatherings be no more than 10 people.

The emergency funding Missouri is receiving for the COVID-19 pandemic is allotted to the state based on census population data. In order to be adequately funded, Missouri must first be adequately counted.
April 1st is Census Day. These are challenging times, and while taking part in the 2020 Census may not currently be at the top of your list, responses to the 2020 Census are more important than ever.
So for the sake of ALL Missourians, be smart, be responsible, and STAY HOME.
We need to get rid of the mentality that people are “stuck” at  home. You are SAFE at home.
No matter where you live or how old you are, EVERYONE should be staying home as much as possible. By not following these orders, you are putting yourself and everyone around you at risk.

As I have said many times, the COVID-19 situation changes EVERY DAY. Every day, we are constantly re-evaluating and looking at all possible options.
 
But again, the most important step anyone can take right now is STAYING HOME.

These are not easy decisions, but just as families and businesses have to balance their budgets and make hard decisions, we are doing the same. This is the right thing to do to make sure our budget is balanced and we are financially prepared to deal with the impacts of COVID-19.

Of the $180 million, I assure you these restrictions are absolutely necessary and include funding for several departments – many of which are priorities of my own administration. In addition, the Judiciary & Secretary of State have worked to identify savings in their own budgets.
In addition to the $180 million we’re restricting in the budget, we are hopeful we may be able to use an additional $315 million dollars in federal funding this year to help with the shortfall.
To ensure our budget is balanced and we have the funds to combat COVID-19 going forward, we are planning to restrict $180 million dollars in spending.

Between now and June 31st, we are estimating an over $500 million shortfall.
 
We have had to take a hard look at our budget and make some very difficult decisions.
While we still do not know the true impact of COVID-19 on the economy, we do know that we have to act NOW.

When we began this fiscal year, we anticipated economic growth, and we had based our budget on that growth. COVID-19 has had serious impacts on our anticipated economic growth, and now we are expecting significant revenue declines.

However, the impact of COVID-19 has already been hard felt in our economy.
 
More people are staying home. Businesses operations have been limited, many people have lost their jobs, and state revenues are down.
The General Assembly has also shown great restraint and leadership in passing conservative budgets, and by working together, we have been able to ensure that our state is financially sound.

Last year, we were able to leave $100 million dollars on the bottom line in order to respond to any unexpected revenue declines.
 
We also proposed to do the same for next year, ensuring
another year of responsible state budgeting and savings.

Up until this point in my administration, we have been very fortunate to have a booming economy with record low unemployment & high wage growth.
 
Incomes have gone up, & taxes have gone down.
We have, at many times, had more jobs available than we have had people to fill them.
As I said yesterday, COVID-19 is having a serious impact not only on public health, but also our economy.
